It's purely just here are some
thoughts that they can use to

00:04:02.190 --> 00:04:03.440
improve the app.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:06.890
This is the first screen that
we're going to take a look at.

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:09.400
We're going to take a look at
about three or four screens.

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:11.620
This is basically the
onboarding process.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:15.530
And it's kind of a wizard, where
it takes you through the

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.640
different leagues, and lets
you customize what are the

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:19.969
things you want to see
in the app, what are

00:04:19.969 --> 00:04:20.780
you interested in?

00:04:20.780 --> 00:04:22.880
I'm guessing if you're a
football fan, you're not

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:25.260
interested in every single
league out there, because

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:26.160
there are millions.

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:29.520
Even just within the UK, there
are probably hundreds or

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:30.720
thousands or something.

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.240
So you can really customize what
specific leagues you're

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:34.240
interested in.

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:36.565
And then in the later steps, you
actually get to customize

00:04:36.565 --> 00:04:39.700
the notifications, which things
you want to be notified

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:44.070
of in the status bar.

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:45.880
So we took a look
at this screen.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:48.850
And we thought, how can
we make it feel

00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:50.960
a little more Androidy?

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:55.760
And so we came up with a version
that's using a more

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.110
common wizard-like UI.

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:02.360
And I posted some sample code
for this a few months ago.

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:03.740
It was called wizard pager.

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:07.220
So this is using some hints
from that wizard pager,

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:09.570
including things like
having a bottom bar

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:10.970
for Next and Previous.

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:13.640
It's worth noting here that
some folks think, there's

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:15.340
already a back button on the
device, why wouldn't

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:16.460
you just use that?

00:05:16.460 --> 00:05:18.680
Well, I actually had a talk
with our design team, our

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:21.750
Android User Experience team,
and they felt that, in this

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.590
case, this is actually one of
those really weird edge cases

00:05:24.590 --> 00:05:28.000
where you don't actually want to
overload the back button to

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.160
go back in the wizard, since
you have a very apparent

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:33.980
onscreen next affordance.

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:38.390
So Previous and Next at the
bottom, very similar to an OK,

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:41.520
Cancel presentation
in dialogues.

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:43.900
And then for indicating which
step you're looking at,

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:47.910
there's this little strip at the
top that indicates you're

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:51.120
past step one, and now you're
looking at step two.

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:53.170
And step two is highlighted
in green, which is

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:55.090
your current step.

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:58.780
Additionally, we bumped up
the size of the imagery.

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:04.010
And again, in general, we love
to make image concept larger,

00:06:04.010 --> 00:06:06.890
because it's a little
more engaging.

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:10.100
And so we made the country
logo a little larger.

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:12.790
We made the text a
little larger.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:16.060
And then we also used more
hollow style elements for the

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:17.340
check boxes and things
like that.

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:18.760
So some very basic stuff.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:22.320
But overall, we kind of tweaked
the screen to more

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:25.060
prominently highlight
the content.

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:27.880
Actually we had added an action
bar at the top that's

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:30.750
using a different palette, an
inverted palette, so that it

00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:34.930
fades away and feels more like
the part of the system,

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:37.290
Chrome, the system UI, rather
than part of the application

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:40.740
in this case, and a couple
things like that.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:42.750
Before we move on, Nick, is
there anything you wanted to

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:45.120
add to wizards or
onboarding flow?

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:47.600
NICK BUTCHER: No, I just think
while it might seem like

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:49.940
there's very small changes in
the screen, for me it really

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:54.320
works, because the use of more
standard controls really makes

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.620
it a lot easier to appreciate
what's going on on this page.

00:06:56.620 --> 00:06:59.140
And that's very important when
you're talking about the very

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.410
first thing the user's going
to see when they first run

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:02.130
this application.

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:04.200
You've got this small window of
time to convinced the user

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.480
that your application's easy to
use, and they want to keep

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:07.940
it, and it's going
to be useful.

00:07:07.940 --> 00:07:11.030
So I think the little bits
like using the standard

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:13.460
controls and making it
immediately obvious and easy

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:17.190
to pass the screen, as it were,
and understand what it's

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:19.610
offering you, really,
really help here.

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:23.320
Better than this might
even be to offer some

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:24.440
kind of sensible defaults.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:26.500
So you might want to detect
which country they're in and

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:29.150
help them into some sensible
defaults, and then allow the

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:31.660
user to go through this
customization flow at a later

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:35.010
point, because it really is this
very, very crucial time,

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:36.400
the first time a user
runs an app.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:39.160
So the visual changes here
for me are really great.

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:42.170
I mean, the bar at the top on
the original, showing which

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:44.610
step you're currently on, didn't
really speak to me.

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:45.535
It's a quite low contrast.

00:07:45.535 --> 00:07:47.780
You're in the current step, and
there's repeated icons.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.580
ROMAN NURIK: Right, there's just
a little white sliver.

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:53.210
And it's white on a tan
background, so the contrast is

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:54.750
very poor there.

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:56.630
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah, and having
to move your thumb all the way

00:07:56.630 --> 00:07:59.100
to the top corner to
hit Next and so on.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:02.310
So I think the small changes
that we've made really, really

00:08:02.310 --> 00:08:07.210
make this screen much easier
to understand and to use.

00:08:07.210 --> 00:08:08.980
ROMAN NURIK: And one other thing
I wanted to mention is,

00:08:08.980 --> 00:08:12.930
in general, we actually have
a very good document in the

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:17.320
design guide that talks about
help as well as tutorials.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:20.280
So in general, the guidance
there is actually if a user

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:22.270
doesn't need to make a decision
immediately, if you

00:08:22.270 --> 00:08:25.730
can just stick with a default,
and that's OK for 60%, 70% of

00:08:25.730 --> 00:08:27.800
people, let them skip
the tutorial.

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:30.380
You don't want to force them
to go through something.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:35.100
In this case, you could argue
that the user has to choose

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:37.730
what they're interested in,
because otherwise you won't be

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:41.220
able to present them any
sort of useful data.

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:44.560
But as soon as you're done, as
soon as you're done specifying

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:46.050
the one thing you're
interested in,

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:47.230
let the user skip.

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:49.630
So find some way to
provide a skip or

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:52.550
get started now function.

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:56.390
So let's move on to the next
screen which we looked at,

00:08:56.390 --> 00:08:59.570
which was the list of matches.

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:03.350
And so on the left here, you
see the list of matches.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:05.560
And you'll notice that there's
actually a number of different

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:06.530
ways you can sort this.

00:09:06.530 --> 00:09:08.390
You can sort this
by the league.

00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:12.700
You can sort is by time, and a
number of different things.

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:15.300
We'll show this on the next
screen, but there's also the

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:17.640
navigation drawer on the left.

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:19.680
And we'll talk about
that in a bit.

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:23.250
There is also this button here
that filters by only live now

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.540
matches, so only matches that
are currently live.

00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:28.860
And then you can swipe left and
right between yesterday

00:09:28.860 --> 00:09:30.615
and tomorrow, as
well as today.

00:09:30.615 --> 00:09:34.020
The issue I found with this is
that there's not actually a

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:36.980
yesterday minus 1 and a
yesterday minus 2 and so on.

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:38.750
You can only see those
three days.

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:42.520
It may be because of some sort
of policy thing, or maybe they

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:44.070
just don't have the data.

00:09:44.070 --> 00:09:48.210
But in that case, do you
really need a set of

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:49.790
scrollable tabs?

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:53.440
So what we decided to do here
was we kind of re-imagined

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:56.730
what it would look like with
just tabs in a slightly

00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:57.810
different color scheme.

00:09:57.810 --> 00:10:02.400
We actually tweaked the color
scheme from a very deep

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:06.210
orangey brown to a slightly
more subdued brown.

00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:11.240
And then we used, I call it a
turf green, as the highlight,

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:13.620
as the single accent that's
used throughout.

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:19.970
So this darkish desaturated
brown combined with the green

00:10:19.970 --> 00:10:23.180
gives it a more earthy,
a little more

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:26.600
simpler feel, I'd say.

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:29.760
And then we also switched over
to the fixed tabs to show

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:30.990
yesterday, today,
and tomorrow.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:32.190
And again, you should
still be able to

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:34.120
swipe between the three.

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:38.180
We also removed the navigation
drawer and switched to an

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:38.910
action bar spinner.

00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:41.980
And I'll talk about that
on the next slide.

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:44.250
And then we used a slightly
different presentation for the

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:48.010
actual content, the actual
matches themselves.

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:50.710
We slightly made the
live matches a

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:52.480
little bit more prominent.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:55.500
In that left column here, you'll
see that live matches

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:57.390
are kind of highlighted
in green.

00:10:57.390 --> 00:11:00.410
And then any time you have set
up notifications for an

00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:02.930
individual match, if you decided
that I really want to

00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:06.890
follow what happens in this
match, you see a little green

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:08.220
tick at the very top right.

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:09.680
And it's not interactive.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:12.520
It's probably worth mentioning
that if you wanted to make

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:16.010
this interactive, have a
notification button right in

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:18.500
line with the list item, this
should look very different.

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:20.820
But this is a very clear
signal that it's not

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:22.180
interactive, it's purely
an indicator.

