00:22:08.240 --> 00:22:09.850
So Launcher Icons.

00:22:09.850 --> 00:22:12.310
Basically the Android Design
Guide has a little bit about

00:22:12.310 --> 00:22:13.510
icons in general.

00:22:13.510 --> 00:22:15.650
So an icon is a graphic that
takes up a small portion of

00:22:15.650 --> 00:22:19.650
screen real estate, provides a
quick intuitive representation

00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:21.960
of an action, a status,
or your app.

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:27.000
So really in the space of 48 by
48 dips, you have to make

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.120
the best use of that space to
represent what your app does,

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:31.170
what it means.

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:33.350
And whether that's an icon
representing your brand, if

00:22:33.350 --> 00:22:37.070
you have an existing service,
or if it's a utility app in

00:22:37.070 --> 00:22:40.570
that space, try as best as
possible to represent what the

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:44.180
user will benefit from once
they use your app.

00:22:44.180 --> 00:22:46.210
So one example is there was a
little side project that I

00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:47.810
worked on that was
just basically a

00:22:47.810 --> 00:22:50.610
single text box notepad.

00:22:50.610 --> 00:22:53.560
And the icon was literally
just the text box.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:56.880
It showed a little cursor, and
it showed the text box.

00:22:56.880 --> 00:22:58.170
So you can do things
like that.

00:22:58.170 --> 00:23:04.350
You don't necessarily have to
use this synecdoche to take

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:07.940
this very abstract idea and
compress it down into a single

00:23:07.940 --> 00:23:09.450
little object.

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:12.260
But certainly that's
one possible way.

00:23:12.260 --> 00:23:15.470
So let's look at some guidelines
on Launcher Icons.

00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:21.630
Again, the actual asset size
is 48 by 48 dips In XHDPI,

00:23:21.630 --> 00:23:23.370
that's 96 by 96.

00:23:23.370 --> 00:23:26.890
For tablets, for Nexus 10
specifically, you should

00:23:26.890 --> 00:23:33.420
provide an XXHDPI icon, and
that's 144 by 144 pixels.

00:23:33.420 --> 00:23:38.850
Also, when you upload your app
to Google Play, it requests a

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:41.620
large app icon so that it can
show it in all its beautiful

00:23:41.620 --> 00:23:43.930
glory on tablets and
phones and so on.

00:23:43.930 --> 00:23:46.240
And that should be 512
by 512 pixels.

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:50.760
And generally what we've found
is you can probably start by

00:23:50.760 --> 00:23:52.750
designing a 512 by 512.

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:56.050
I actually use 576 by 576,
for some reason.

00:23:56.050 --> 00:23:58.990
But you can start with that,
and then slowly scale down.

00:23:58.990 --> 00:24:01.420
It's generally a good idea to
start large and scale down,

00:24:01.420 --> 00:24:03.820
rather than vice versa.

00:24:03.820 --> 00:24:06.000
And then in terms of padding,
this is something that's

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.890
definitely changed over
the years for Android.

00:24:08.890 --> 00:24:11.620
We used to request a fairly
large padding region.

00:24:11.620 --> 00:24:14.350
But these days, you should
really just use either the

00:24:14.350 --> 00:24:17.110
full image size, meaning no
padding, or if you have a

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:21.830
very, very square icon, then try
to use about three dips of

00:24:21.830 --> 00:24:23.550
padding, give or take.

00:24:23.550 --> 00:24:24.360
It's really up to you.

00:24:24.360 --> 00:24:27.800
But in general, try to make it
fit in nicely with the rest of

00:24:27.800 --> 00:24:30.250
the system icons, as well
as third party icons.

00:24:30.250 --> 00:24:32.450
And those are generally going
to take up the full image

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:35.400
size, or have about one to
three dips of padding.

00:24:38.070 --> 00:24:41.140
Before we move on and fly
through this, Nick, any other

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:42.980
comments on launchers?

00:24:42.980 --> 00:24:44.062
NICK BUTCHER: No, you're
nailing it.

00:24:44.062 --> 00:24:44.530
Go for it.

00:24:44.530 --> 00:24:46.010
ROMAN NURIK: All right,
let's do it.

00:24:46.010 --> 00:24:47.820
So a couple more guidelines.

00:24:47.820 --> 00:24:49.120
Try to use a distinct
silhouette.

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:52.540
So don't just stick some
graphic inside of

00:24:52.540 --> 00:24:53.720
a square or a circle.

00:24:53.720 --> 00:24:55.450
That can work for now.

00:24:55.450 --> 00:24:56.610
It can work as a default.

00:24:56.610 --> 00:24:58.350
But try to really use a
distinct silhouette.

00:24:58.350 --> 00:25:01.070
And we'll show good examples
of that in a bit.

00:25:01.070 --> 00:25:03.330
Also, keep it simple
at the top.

00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:07.420
Make sure that your icon, when
it's scaled down, it still

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:09.730
means something. it
still makes sense.

00:25:09.730 --> 00:25:12.610
But at the very micro level,
feel free to add details, like

00:25:12.610 --> 00:25:15.330
noise or subtle drop shadows,
and things like

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.270
that, as you see fit.

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:18.970
And then, very important,
don't try

00:25:18.970 --> 00:25:20.450
to mimic other platforms.

00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:24.310
So if you have an existing app
on Windows Phone, or an iPhone

00:25:24.310 --> 00:25:27.310
iOS, don't just simply
copy over your icon.

00:25:27.310 --> 00:25:29.990
It's OK to copy over the general
idea for the icon.

00:25:29.990 --> 00:25:31.640
But make sure that it fits
well with the rest of the

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:34.750
system and fits in with
the guidelines.

00:25:34.750 --> 00:25:37.400
Actually, before we look at
